messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path:
/v1/book/{id}

All methods acceptable:
- all_methods: false

Per-method acceptance (based on the code):
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- The blueprint registration chain in app/__init__.py registers the v1 blueprint with url_prefix="/v1". In app/api/v1/__init__.py the v1 blueprint registers the book blueprint with url_prefix="/book". The route in app/api/v1/book.py is declared as @book_api.route("/<int:id>"), so the combined full path is /v1 + /book + /<int:id> â†’ /v1/book/{id} (path parameter shown as {id}).
- The get_book view uses @book_api.route("/<int:id>") with no methods argument, so the code defines a GET handler for that path (hence GET: true).
- The code explicitly defines other handlers for the same path with methods=["PUT"] (update_book) and methods=["DELETE"] (delete_book), so PUT and DELETE are accepted for this path (PUT: true, DELETE: true).
- There is no explicit POST or PATCH or TRACE route for /<int:id> in the code, so those methods are not accepted for this endpoint (POST, PATCH, TRACE: false).
- HEAD and OPTIONS are not explicitly listed in the route decorators in the source code. Per the requirement to judge based on the code (not on runtime/framework implicit behavior), they are reported as false.
